(464, 5, '2014-12-29 10:35:09', '2014-12-29 10:35:09', 'You may remember the film that gives name to the head of this text. "Panic Room", directed by David Fincher always surprising, looked out the charts in 2002 with Jodie Foster in the main character role and a very young Kristen Stewart playing her daughter.\r\n\r\nWhen three intruders assaulted her home, mother and daughter are enclosed within the ''panic room'' of the house, with the particularity that what the intruders are looking for is inside that room. From there we will see how the characters in Foster and Stewart control many mechanisms in the home managing the system from the room, playing in his favor while the walls protect them.\r\n\r\nLike everything in fiction, some reality exists in "Panic Room" ... something that today more than ever, is the most evident with the implementation of the Smart Home. The automation of a home is able to control an entire home, going far beyond from turn-off devices. The most basic concept of home automation give much play in this regard, but the premises that govern <strong>Domocracy</strong>, with it open source philosophy, revolutionizing the methodology of smart home, bringing further from the mere susceptibility to master the millimeter every corner of the home.\r\n\r\nIn this sense, the "room" is out walls and fits in our hands, something very seductive when you consider the possibilities of "home automation" as far as security is concerned. Close doors, secure windows, turn on lights, trigger alarms ... this is just the tip of the iceberg.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Panic room ', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'panic-room', '', '', '2014-12-29 10:54:09', '2014-12-29 10:54:09', '', 0, 'http://www.domocracytech.com/?p=464', 0, 'post', '', 0),
